# Column: AGE

# Plotting a box plot to check presence of outliers.
sns.boxplot(x=continuous_valued_columns[0], data=dataframe)

# Calculate individual outlier values  

dataframe1.sort_values(by=[continuous_valued_columns[0]])
c=0
q1, q3= np.percentile(dataframe1[continuous_valued_columns[0]],[25,75])
iqr = q3 - q1
lower_bound = q1 -(1.5 * iqr) 
upper_bound = q3 +(1.5 * iqr) 

outliers = [x for x in dataframe1[continuous_valued_columns[0]] if x < lower_bound or x > upper_bound]
for i in set(outliers):
     c = c+outliers.count(i)
    
print("The count of outliers for column ", continuous_valued_columns[0]," is: ",c)

#Solution: As the data set is biased (since the number of entries of people not having subscribed to term deposit is far
#greater than the number of people who have subscribed for it) the model which has the best F1 score is supposed to be 
#the best model.

#The best model out of the three is KNN with a high F1 Score and high recall value.
# I think KNN works best for this data set due to the high value of co-relation between certain data attributes. 
# KNN uses the technique of trying to find similarities between data points.
# We have not used any hyper parameter optimization so that we could comapre the models/algortithms in a same way and the 
#training cost of all the models seems to be equal.
#Therefore it seems to perform best on this data.  
# SVM also has a comparitively good value of F1 Score but has low recall value for imbalanced class.

from sklearn import tree
def DTree_classifier(x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test):

from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingClassifier

def Bagging_Classifer(x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test):

  print(confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred))

 from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier
 
 def Gradient_Boosting_Classifier(x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test):
  gb = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators = 50, learning_rate = 0.09, max_depth=5)
  gb.fit(x_train, y_train)
  y_pred=gb.predict(x_test)

# Ada Boosting

from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostClassifier
def AdaBoost_Classifier(x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test):
  dt_model = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion = 'entropy' )  
  abcl = AdaBoostClassifier(base_estimator=dt_model, n_estimators=50)
  abcl = abcl.fit(x_train, y_train)
  y_pred=abcl.predict(x_test)
  print(classification_report(y_test,y_pred))
  print(confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred))
  print('F1-Score:', f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted'))
